00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.480
is sleep and sort
of how does it work

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:14.980
to give you kind of the basic
parameters from which to work.

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:16.854
So this slide looks a
little bit complicated,

00:02:16.854 --> 00:02:17.730
but it's really not.

00:02:17.730 --> 00:02:20.850
So it turns out that there
are two distinct systems

00:02:20.850 --> 00:02:22.600
in the brain for sleep.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:24.467
One of them is a drive,
kind of like hunger.

00:02:24.467 --> 00:02:25.050
So I'm hungry.

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:25.410
I'm hungry.

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:25.950
I'm hungry.

00:02:25.950 --> 00:02:28.440
I eat something, and that
hunger begins to dissipate.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:30.720
The same holds true with sleep.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:33.540
What we find is that there's
something in our brain

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:35.040
that makes us
sleepier and sleepier,

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:36.650
and it's called adenosine.

00:02:36.650 --> 00:02:39.870
Adenosine is actually
a byproduct of cells,

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:41.640
so when a cell eats
a piece of glucose,

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:43.050
something comes
out the back end.

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:45.354
Part of what comes out
the back end is adenosine,

00:02:45.354 --> 00:02:47.520
and adenosine works its way
through the bloodstream,

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:50.460
gets into the brain, and it
goes to a very specific receptor

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:52.297
site specifically for adenosine.

00:02:52.297 --> 00:02:53.880
And as that builds
up, we get sleepier

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:55.410
and sleepier and sleepier.

00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:57.480
Now why all this talk
about neurochemistry?

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:00.120
Well, it turns out that if you
look at the molecular structure

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:02.580
of adenosine, and you look
at the molecular structure

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:06.630
of caffeine, they're
off by one molecule.

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:07.130
Right?

00:03:07.130 --> 00:03:09.860
So here's what happens is
when you're getting tired,

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:12.440
and you're putting down the
coffee or the energy drinks

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.150
or what have you,
that actually goes,

00:03:14.150 --> 00:03:16.940
and it fits really nicely
into that receptor site,

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:18.620
and it blocks the adenosine.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:21.170
But then once your brain
burns through the caffeine,

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:23.090
the adenosine comes
flooding in, and that's

00:03:23.090 --> 00:03:25.001
where you get that
caffeine crash,

00:03:25.001 --> 00:03:27.500
because it's all that adenosine
and that's actually now made

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:29.120
its way through the floodgates.

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:30.530
So that's sleep drive.

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:34.252
We want adenosine to raise
at a very consistent level,

00:03:34.252 --> 00:03:35.210
get to a certain point.

00:03:35.210 --> 00:03:37.220
Usually, around 10:30,
11:00 o'clock at night,

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:38.900
it kind of reaches
its max, and that's

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:40.580
when most people fall asleep.

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:42.360
But that's not the
only aspect of sleep.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.070
There's also a circadian rhythm.

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:45.530
So the circadian
rhythm is a lot--

00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:47.990
it's really your
biological clock.

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:51.140
And what I mean by that is
kind of like with hunger

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:53.330
as well, so you ever
notice how you get hungry

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:56.360
with breakfast, lunch, and
dinner about the same time?

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.200
So the same holds
true with sleep

00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:00.230
is you have this
circadian system,

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:02.780
and this actually makes
you want to get sleepier

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:06.731
at particular times
irrespective of adenosine.

00:04:06.731 --> 00:04:08.730
So how many people in
here, by a raise of hands,

00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:12.440
have ever had the situation,
where you're exhausted?

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:14.270
You are absolutely dog tired.

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:16.820
You've had the worst,
horrible, crazy day,

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:19.519
and you're physically-- all
you can do is crawl into bed.

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:21.709
And you get into bed,
let's say, at 8 o'clock

00:04:21.709 --> 00:04:23.966
at night, because you're
just so exhausted.

00:04:23.966 --> 00:04:25.340
How many people
in here have ever

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:26.960
had that situation
occur for them?

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:28.620
OK, literally
everybody in the room.

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:30.380
Now let me ask you this.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:32.120
Do you fall asleep?

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:33.022
Almost never.

00:04:33.022 --> 00:04:35.480
Your brain just starts going
and going and going and going.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:39.396
That's a situation where your
adenosine is very, very high,

00:04:39.396 --> 00:04:40.770
but your circadian
rhythm is off,

00:04:40.770 --> 00:04:42.860
because you went
to bed too early.

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:46.760
One of the number one things
that my insomnia patients do

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:48.590
is go to bed too
early, which sounds

00:04:48.590 --> 00:04:50.330
completely counterintuitive.

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:52.370
Like if I've got
insomnia, and I'm tired,

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:54.860
maybe I can get in bed
and catch up on my sleep.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:57.050
It doesn't really work that way.

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.220
Same holds true for
the drive situation.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:02.360
So how many people in here
have had a nice, big dinner,

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:03.950
and they've sat
down on the couch

00:05:03.950 --> 00:05:05.810
just because they were
watching a little TV,

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:08.185
and before they knew it, they
were out for about an hour,

00:05:08.185 --> 00:05:10.370
took an unscheduled nap?

00:05:10.370 --> 00:05:13.730
Then when you go back and go
to bed at your normal bed time,

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:14.840
what happens?

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:16.970
You can't sleep, because
you've actually reduced

00:05:16.970 --> 00:05:18.200
sleep drive at that time.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:20.480
Your circadian rhythm
is ready to sleep,

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:22.100
but your drive is
down, because you

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:24.800
got rid of some of that
adenosine during your nap.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:26.810
So we've all had
both of these systems

00:05:26.810 --> 00:05:28.610
kind of go a little
kooky for us,

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:30.800
and so the goal here is
to be able to get people

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:34.140
to understand the drive,
understand the rhythm,

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:38.320
and when those two are in
balance, that's when we sleep.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:43.085
So it turns out that all of our
hormones lead a circadian life.

00:05:43.085 --> 00:05:43.960
So what is circadian?

00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:47.320
It's a 24-hour cycle, but
yet every hormone in our body

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:49.512
is very, very predictable.

00:05:49.512 --> 00:05:51.470
So if you look here on
the slides, you can see,

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:55.030
for example, cortisol follows
a very predictable schedule.

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:57.580
So does adrenaline,
and so does melatonin.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:01.240
Kind of interesting-- melatonin
is almost the exact opposite

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:02.050
of cortisol.

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:04.180
But it actually
corresponds very well

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:05.660
with core body temperature.

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:07.180
So as core body
temperature lowers,

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.610
we see melatonin rising.

00:06:09.610 --> 00:06:14.290
These are very, very predictable
situations in the body.

00:06:14.290 --> 00:06:16.240
So why is that
important, and how can we

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:18.490
use that to leverage
it for ourselves?

00:06:18.490 --> 00:06:21.910
Well, has anybody in here
ever been called an early bird

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:22.570
before?

00:06:22.570 --> 00:06:24.880
Like to get up really
early, 5:30, 6 o'clock?

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:25.540
OK.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:26.860
How about night owls?

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.140
I'm actually the night
owl side of things.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:30.334
So interesting.

00:06:30.334 --> 00:06:31.375
Yeah, I know you are too.

00:06:31.375 --> 00:06:34.612
So it's interesting when you
start to think about that idea.

00:06:34.612 --> 00:06:36.820
So when you think about an
early bird or a night owl,

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:39.370
if we actually looked
at their melatonin,

00:06:39.370 --> 00:06:43.840
it actually falls under
the same wave form--

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:45.875
however, at different times.

00:06:45.875 --> 00:06:47.500
So if we look here,
and we see the red,

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.150
that's an early
bird, and the blue--

00:06:49.150 --> 00:06:50.230
that's a night owl.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:52.660
It turns out that even though
they have the same melatonin

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:56.080
curve, they're happening
at very different times

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:59.230
in their own
24-hour cycle, which

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:01.900
is very, very interesting when
you start to think about it.

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:05.920
So Michael, you're telling
me that if I'm a night owl,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:10.600
and I wake up at 7 o'clock,
6:30 in the morning,

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:11.350
what's going on?

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:13.760
My melatonin faucet is
still running, running,

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:16.464
running, whereas if I'm
an early bird, it's not.

00:07:16.464 --> 00:07:18.880
So this is why, for all of you
people who are night owls--

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:20.920
raise your hand again
if you're a night owl.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.590
This is why mornings suck.

00:07:23.590 --> 00:07:24.370
Bottom line.

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:26.290
There's nothing fun
about getting up

00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:28.510
in the mornings for you
people because of this.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:31.480
Your melatonin is
actually still going.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:32.980
It's still moving
in that direction,

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:35.830
and that's where that
morning fog is coming from,

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:37.870
whereas for all of
you early birds,

00:07:37.870 --> 00:07:39.820
mornings are a breeze for you.

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:41.770
However, doing
stuff late at night

00:07:41.770 --> 00:07:43.910
doesn't always work out so well.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:46.505
So what I did was I
created a quiz for people

00:07:46.505 --> 00:07:48.130
to be able to tell,
because by the way,

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:51.116
there aren't just two of these
what we call chronotypes.

00:07:51.116 --> 00:07:52.990
So first of all, has
everybody in here gotten

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:55.100
an opportunity to take the quiz?

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:55.600
No?

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:57.430
OK, so if you
haven't-- you have, OK.

00:07:57.430 --> 00:07:59.650
So if you haven't had a
chance to take the quiz,

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:06.220
go to thepowerofwhenquiz.com,
and it's available right now.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:09.250
You go on there, and it takes
like literally two minutes

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:09.846
to do it.

00:08:09.846 --> 00:08:12.220
And then you'll be able to
learn what your chronotype is.

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.050
And I'm going to go through all
of the different chronotypes

00:08:14.050 --> 00:08:14.740
right now.

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:17.251
But the quiz is a
little weird, because it

00:08:17.251 --> 00:08:19.750
doesn't take into-- it doesn't
ask you some of the questions

00:08:19.750 --> 00:08:20.840
that you might imagine.

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:23.050
So it takes into account
things like personality.

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:25.030
For example, there are
certain chronotypes

00:08:25.030 --> 00:08:27.160
that are more introverted
and certain chronotypes

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:28.604
that are more extroverted.

00:08:28.604 --> 00:08:30.520
It takes into account
things like sleep timing

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:32.230
and preference, which
would make sense.

00:08:32.230 --> 00:08:34.854
That would be kind of one of the
things that we should look at.

00:08:34.854 --> 00:08:36.940
And then it takes into
account sleep drive.

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:40.750
So it turns out that all of this
is genetically predetermined

00:08:40.750 --> 00:08:44.620
based on something
called your PER3 gene.

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:47.170
Believe it or not, there are
over 80 different markers

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:50.395
for sleep in the
genetics of the--

00:08:50.395 --> 00:08:52.102
if you looked at the
whole microbiome,

00:08:52.102 --> 00:08:53.560
and you looked at
all of that area,

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:56.080
you would actually find
that there are actually 84,

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.274
I think it is, genetic
markers out there

00:08:58.274 --> 00:08:59.440
looking at the human genome.

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:01.600
But the PER3 gene
is the one that's

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:04.390
the most really in there for
what we're talking about here.

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:06.250
And it has a lot to
do with sleep drive.

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:08.050
So when you're taking
the quiz, that's

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:09.758
what the questions
are going to be about.

00:09:09.758 --> 00:09:12.570
And it'll give you what's called
a personalized ChronoCategory,

00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:14.440
or what I call a chronotype.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:17.080
So it turns out that
there's four, not two.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:19.210
And if you look
historically, we've

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:20.470
always known about the two.

00:09:20.470 --> 00:09:22.480
Actually, there have been
quizzes and assessment tools

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:25.146
around for quite a while looking
at the early bird and the night

00:09:25.146 --> 00:09:27.910
owl, but not necessarily
people in the middle,

00:09:27.910 --> 00:09:30.920
and also not necessarily
people with insomnia.

00:09:30.920 --> 00:09:32.710
So it turns out that
people with insomnia

00:09:32.710 --> 00:09:35.680
actually have a very
different genetic makeup

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:37.570
in certain cases,
and a lot of it

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:39.357
is actually genetically
predetermined.

00:09:39.357 --> 00:09:41.440
So it's important for you
to be able to understand

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.190
and recognize that you
might fall into one

00:09:43.190 --> 00:09:44.584
of those categories as well.

00:09:44.584 --> 00:09:46.000
So what I thought
I would do is go

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.860
through each of the
chronotypes while people

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:50.680
out there taking the
quiz and learning

00:09:50.680 --> 00:09:52.457
what their chronotype is.

00:09:52.457 --> 00:09:54.040
That way they can
get an understanding

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:56.600
of some of the things that
are going on with them.

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:00.080
So first one are
what I call lions.

