So I replaced the vernacular
of birds to mammals.

00:10:04.460 --> 00:10:06.330
So first of all,
why did I do that?

00:10:06.330 --> 00:10:07.520
Well, because I'm a mammal.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:08.510
I'm not a bird.

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:10.640
And I really thought it
would make more sense

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:12.200
to look at different mammals.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.300
And by the way,
these animals all

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:17.270
actually have the chronotype
that we're talking about.

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:20.202
So lions have a tendency to--
their first kill is at dawn.

00:10:20.202 --> 00:10:22.160
They wake up very, very
early, and that's where

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:23.870
they do most of their hunting.

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:26.600
But my lions as a group,
not as the animal,

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:29.780
but now as all of us would be,
are pretty interesting folks.

00:10:29.780 --> 00:10:33.390
They make up about 15%, 15%
to 20% of the population.

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:35.420
And these are my early
morning optimists

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:38.720
with what we consider to
be a medium sleep drive.

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:39.860
These are my go-getters.

00:10:39.860 --> 00:10:41.510
These are my COOs.

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:42.720
These are the managers.

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:45.170
These are people who are
really good at asking people

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:47.270
to do certain things and
trying to move people

00:10:47.270 --> 00:10:49.220
through a process.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:52.010
They're likely to prioritize
health and fitness.

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:54.590
These are people who like
to do the marathons, who

00:10:54.590 --> 00:10:56.281
like to do the triathlons.

00:10:56.281 --> 00:10:58.280
These are your CrossFitters,
your Tough Mudders,

00:10:58.280 --> 00:10:59.900
people like that.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.150
But they also have a very
interesting tendency.

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.842
They like to make a
plan almost every day,

00:11:04.842 --> 00:11:06.050
and they like to stick to it.

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:07.790
So they like to do the
first thing, and then

00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:09.740
the second thing, and then
the third thing, and then

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:10.490
the fourth thing.

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:12.715
They do not like to
derivate whatsoever.

00:11:12.715 --> 00:11:14.340
So how many people
in here, by the way,

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:17.300
are a lion or an early bird?

00:11:17.300 --> 00:11:19.684
So does any of that kind
of ring true for you guys?

00:11:19.684 --> 00:11:22.100
Is that sort of something that
sort of makes sense to you,

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:24.641
that you have a tendency to get
up very early in the morning,

00:11:24.641 --> 00:11:27.230
follow that plan, be
able to kind of be more

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:28.520
on the leadership side?

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:31.062
Is that something that people
find that resonates with them?

00:11:31.062 --> 00:11:33.020
Also, we know that these
people have a tendency

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:35.330
to go to bed really early.

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:37.700
So these are my
8:30, 9 o'clockers,

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:40.310
because they're getting
up at 5:30 in the morning.

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:42.980
So it's not an uncommon
situation for these people.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:45.830
Now I've had a lot of people
who are lions turn to me,

00:11:45.830 --> 00:11:48.860
and they say, I feel so guilty,
because I can never make it

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:50.330
through dinner and a movie.

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:52.460
Dinner is fine, but the
movie-- forget about it.

00:11:52.460 --> 00:11:53.480
I am out cold.

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:56.060
I had one person tell me
at my most recent lecture

00:11:56.060 --> 00:11:58.760
that they actually go
to the movie early,

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:00.890
so they do like a
5 o'clock movie,

00:12:00.890 --> 00:12:02.510
and then they go to
dinner afterwards,

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:03.860
because it's the only way
that they can actually

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:06.290
see any of the cinema
that they want to see,

00:12:06.290 --> 00:12:09.810
because otherwise, they're
out cold every single time.

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:11.220
So let's talk about bears.

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:14.430
So bears make up about
50%, 55% of the population.

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:16.474
So one in two people is a bear.

00:12:16.474 --> 00:12:18.140
Now before I talk
about bears, remember,

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:20.480
you can actually lean
more towards the line,

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:22.160
yet still be a
bear, or lean more

00:12:22.160 --> 00:12:23.780
towards what I call
a wolf, and still

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:26.300
be a bear, because there are
hybrids that are out there.

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:28.037
But these are my
people who actually

00:12:28.037 --> 00:12:29.870
have a very healthy
sleep drive, and they're

00:12:29.870 --> 00:12:31.790
what I call solar sleepers.

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:35.960
So these people have a tendency
to follow our main schedule.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:39.205
By the way, being a bear is
the best chronotype to be.

00:12:39.205 --> 00:12:41.330
Most people actually tell
me that they would rather

00:12:41.330 --> 00:12:44.030
be a lion, and they have
what I call lion envy.

00:12:44.030 --> 00:12:47.030
I'm not sure if that's
really the best way to be.

00:12:47.030 --> 00:12:50.870
The world really operates
on a bear's schedule.

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:54.500
And so that's why we have
9:00 to 5:00 work schedules.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:57.620
This is why carpools and buses
go in their certain schedules.

00:12:57.620 --> 00:13:00.290
This is why literally
everything that we do kind of

00:13:00.290 --> 00:13:02.990
runs in this sort of what
we call a solar schedule.

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:06.980
So it's much easier
for bears in general.

00:13:06.980 --> 00:13:08.450
They get the work
done in society.

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:09.824
They have a tendency
to really be

00:13:09.824 --> 00:13:12.057
able to accomplish a
whole lot, as well as

00:13:12.057 --> 00:13:13.640
they have a tendency
to be extroverted

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:14.605
and very open-minded.

00:13:14.605 --> 00:13:15.980
So these are the
people that it's

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:19.100
great to hang out with and have
lunch, because they've always

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:20.300
got the funny story to tell.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:21.410
They kind of know
the gossip that's

00:13:21.410 --> 00:13:23.327
going on in the office
or something like that.

00:13:23.327 --> 00:13:25.910
They've probably been the ones
who are watching "The Bachelor"

00:13:25.910 --> 00:13:27.709
and talking about it
with you incessantly,

00:13:27.709 --> 00:13:28.500
that kind of thing.

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:30.740
But they're a lot of fun,
really interesting people,

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:33.620
and again, they make up
a large bulk of society.

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:36.830
And I said most of society is
built around their schedule.

00:13:36.830 --> 00:13:40.330
So wolves-- how many people
are late night people like me?

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:42.250
OK, so I'm a wolf.

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:44.710
I don't go to bed
ever before midnight.

00:13:44.710 --> 00:13:46.660
It's very, very rare.

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:48.220
If it was up to
me, I would sleep

00:13:48.220 --> 00:13:50.679
until 7:30, 8 o'clock each day,
if that were even possible.

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:52.844
And I certainly wouldn't
go to bed at midnight then.

00:13:52.844 --> 00:13:54.940
I'd go to bed at
2:00, because I'm

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:56.884
that kind of a night person.

00:13:56.884 --> 00:13:58.300
And it's very
interesting when you

00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:00.383
start to think about it,
because the world was not

00:14:00.383 --> 00:14:02.260
built for night people,
unless, of course,

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:03.820
you're a shift worker.

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:06.760
But all of us get the
tag of being lazy.

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:09.220
We get the tag of, you're
not a morning person,

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:11.350
and people seem to
schedule meetings for us

00:14:11.350 --> 00:14:15.220
at ungodly hours of the morning,
and it never seems to work out.

00:14:15.220 --> 00:14:17.050
But we happen to be
very creative thinkers.

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:19.860
So wolves are actually
my introverts.

00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:20.972
They're very interesting.

00:14:20.972 --> 00:14:22.930
These are the most creative
people that I have.

00:14:22.930 --> 00:14:25.990
They crave novelty
and risks, and if they

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:29.395
do bother to make a plan,
they never stick to it.

00:14:29.395 --> 00:14:31.020
They'll do the first
thing on the list,

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:32.200
then the sixth
thing on the list,

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:33.783
and then the fourth
thing on the list,

00:14:33.783 --> 00:14:35.830
and so they get distracted
very, very easily,

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:39.710
yet they still get a
lot of things done.

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:41.920
I would say these are
my authors, my actors,

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:44.970
my musicians, people like that.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:47.177
They become deeply
loyal friends, too.

00:14:47.177 --> 00:14:48.760
These are the people
that will happily

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:50.218
stay up all night
with you and talk

00:14:50.218 --> 00:14:51.970
with you, because they can.

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:54.160
It doesn't bother them
to stay up all night.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.080
And they're really great people.

00:14:56.080 --> 00:14:58.540
Dolphins are my
problem children.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:00.460
So did anybody in
here take the quiz--

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:01.294
were they a dolphin?

00:15:01.294 --> 00:15:03.085
Do they want to raise
and their hand admit?

00:15:03.085 --> 00:15:03.610
OK.

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.832
So my dolphins are my people
who don't sleep very well.

00:15:06.832 --> 00:15:09.040
They have difficulty either
falling asleep or staying

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:10.690
sleep most of the time.

00:15:10.690 --> 00:15:13.540
Not every dolphin is like this,
but I do have that happen.

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:17.420
These are highly, highly
intelligent people,

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:19.780
but they have very erratic
sleep schedules, like I said.

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:22.810
And sometimes they've
already tried multiple things

00:15:22.810 --> 00:15:24.610
to help them with their sleep.

00:15:24.610 --> 00:15:29.770
And so a lot of this
vernacular comes from my work

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:30.700
as a sleep specialist.

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:32.491
So I'm an actively
practicing sleep doctor.

00:15:32.491 --> 00:15:34.300
I've been practicing
for 17 years.

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:35.731
And my specialty is insomnia.

00:15:35.731 --> 00:15:37.480
And one of the things
that was interesting

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:40.150
is I had a patient come
to me, and she said,

00:15:40.150 --> 00:15:41.140
I'm a terrible sleeper.

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:42.556
So I started walking
down the road

00:15:42.556 --> 00:15:44.620
of cognitive behavioral
therapy with her.

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:48.160
And we tried just about
everything, and nothing worked.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:50.440
And it was a complete
and total failure,

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:52.960
which is kind of rare when
you start to understand more

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:55.540
about the reasoning behind
what goes on with people

00:15:55.540 --> 00:15:56.860
who have sleep problems.

00:15:56.860 --> 00:15:59.110
And so I brought
her in, and I said,

00:15:59.110 --> 00:16:00.790
let's try to figure
out what's going on.

00:16:00.790 --> 00:16:03.790
And she said, well, it's not
that I can't fall asleep,

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:05.980
and it's not that I
can't stay asleep.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:08.770
She said, it's that I
sleep at the wrong time.

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:10.900
And so then I started
thinking about my kids.

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:12.790
So my daughter is
here with me today.

00:16:12.790 --> 00:16:15.490
My son and her have the
exact same sleep pattern.

00:16:15.490 --> 00:16:18.250
If it was up to them, they
would go to bed at 2:00,

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:20.080
and they would
sleep until 12:00.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:22.330
And this is what happens in
our house on the weekends.

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:23.939
Anybody in here have teenagers?

00:16:23.939 --> 00:16:25.980
So yeah, you know exactly
what I'm talking about.

00:16:25.980 --> 00:16:27.790
It's incredible.

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:28.990
And so they're wolves.

00:16:28.990 --> 00:16:30.340
And so I started to
think about this patient.

00:16:30.340 --> 00:16:31.506
I discovered, you know what?

00:16:31.506 --> 00:16:32.890
She's actually a wolf.

00:16:32.890 --> 00:16:35.350
And so what I did
was I asked her boss,

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:37.155
can we change her work schedule?

00:16:37.155 --> 00:16:38.530
And he was like,
well, you better

00:16:38.530 --> 00:16:40.630
do something quick,
because in about a week,

00:16:40.630 --> 00:16:41.910
I'm going to fire her.

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:42.910
I was like, no pressure.

00:16:42.910 --> 00:16:43.409
Great.

00:16:43.409 --> 00:16:44.260
Fantastic.

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:47.440
So I go in, and I said, all
right, let's go with this.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:49.840
And we changed her work
times so that she came in

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:51.880
at around 10:30,
but she would work

00:16:51.880 --> 00:16:55.570
until about 6:30, 7 o'clock,
so just a shift in her work

00:16:55.570 --> 00:16:56.380
schedule.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:16:58.120
And after a week, I
called the boss back,

00:16:58.120 --> 00:16:59.950
and I said, how'd it go?

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:03.922
He said, I don't know what you
did, but this is fantastic.

00:17:03.922 --> 00:17:05.380
He said her work
product is better.

00:17:05.380 --> 00:17:06.880
She doesn't fall
asleep in meetings.

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:08.284
It's like a miracle.

00:17:08.284 --> 00:17:08.950
So I'm like, oh.

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:10.020
I said, are you
going to fire her?

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.530
He's like, no, no, no,
we're not going to fire her.

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:12.430
Well, great.

00:17:12.430 --> 00:17:14.290
So I called the husband.

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:16.540
Well, I actually called her
to tell her the good news,

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:18.069
and the husband
picks up the phone.

00:17:18.069 --> 00:17:20.194
And he said something to
me that I'll never forget.

00:17:20.194 --> 00:17:23.876
He said, I like my
wife better, which

00:17:23.876 --> 00:17:25.500
I thought was a really
strong statement

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.960
to make, number one, to
somebody he had never

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:28.990
talked to you before.

00:17:28.990 --> 00:17:30.510
But what he was
telling me was is

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:35.590
he now understood a lot
more about her as a person.

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:38.400
And so the power
of when has a lot

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:42.390
to do with when somebody is
on and when somebody is off

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:46.500
and how all of these
hormones work together

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:48.480
in order for people to
understand these things.

00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:51.510
It's really a communication
tool more than anything.

00:17:51.510 --> 00:17:54.089
And what I find is as soon
as one person takes the quiz,

00:17:54.089 --> 00:17:56.130
they have everybody in
their family take the quiz

00:17:56.130 --> 00:17:59.130
and start learning more about,
how can I communicate better

00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:01.080
within my family?

00:18:01.080 --> 00:18:03.224
So again, highly
intelligent, my dolphins

00:18:03.224 --> 00:18:04.390
are superintelligent people.

00:18:04.390 --> 00:18:07.794
They do have a tendency to be
a little obsessive compulsive,

00:18:07.794 --> 00:18:09.210
and sometimes that
gets in the way

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:11.085
of their levels of
productivity, because they

00:18:11.085 --> 00:18:13.440
want it to be perfect
at every juncture.

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:15.327
And that was a little
bit like this woman.

00:18:15.327 --> 00:18:17.160
But it turned out that
she wasn't a dolphin.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:18.480
It turned out that
she was a wolf,

00:18:18.480 --> 00:18:20.313
and once we are able
to change her schedule,

00:18:20.313 --> 00:18:22.960
it actually worked
out quite well.

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:25.320
So who cares about
all this stuff?

00:18:25.320 --> 00:18:28.896
Remember, if you know what your
chronotype is, and then you

00:18:28.896 --> 00:18:30.270
know what your
hormones are going

00:18:30.270 --> 00:18:32.400
to be doing throughout
a particular day,

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:35.490
I can actually match
the times of day

00:18:35.490 --> 00:18:38.040
when your hormones are
at a particular level

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:42.320
where it would be optimal
to do that activity.

00:18:42.320 --> 00:18:43.940
It's actually a matching game.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:45.960
It's super simple.

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:47.720
So this sounds too
good to be true, right?

00:18:47.720 --> 00:18:50.053
How could he possibly be able
to do something like this?

00:18:50.053 --> 00:18:53.150
Well, so I've actually
got over 350 studies

00:18:53.150 --> 00:18:54.170
backing me up on this.

00:18:54.170 --> 00:18:56.160
Now I didn't do 350 studies.

00:18:56.160 --> 00:18:58.460
What I did was I aggregated
data from around the world,

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:02.130
and it turns out that this is
an area called chronobiology,

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:05.330
and it's been studied for
15, almost 20 years now.

00:19:05.330 --> 00:19:07.460
And so we've got a
tremendous amount of data

00:19:07.460 --> 00:19:10.940
at our fingertips to be able
to see, hey, what can we do?

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:13.130
What can we do better,
and at what time

00:19:13.130 --> 00:19:14.750
would it be better to do it?

00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:16.630
So what I thought
I would do is I'd

00:19:16.630 --> 00:19:19.610
take a couple of topics for you
and show you how that works.

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:22.220
Now in the book,
"The Power of When,"

00:19:22.220 --> 00:19:24.300
there's 50 different topics.

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:26.870
So what I did was I went through
my day of every single thing

00:19:26.870 --> 00:19:28.290
that I did during the
day, and I wrote it down.

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:29.870
Then I asked my
wife to do the same.

00:19:29.870 --> 00:19:31.250
Then I asked a couple of
friends to do the same,

00:19:31.250 --> 00:19:33.830
and we came up with roughly
50 different activities.

00:19:33.830 --> 00:19:35.750
But I thought I would
do some on health

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:38.560
and then some in business so
that you could get an idea

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:39.782
sort of what's been going on.

00:19:39.782 --> 00:19:41.240
So I'd start off
with these topics,

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:43.890
and you'll find them
actually quite interesting.

00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:45.620
So first, let's
talk about caffeine.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:48.737
So I've been walking around
Google's campus, and one

00:19:48.737 --> 00:19:50.570
of the things that I
noticed is you're never

00:19:50.570 --> 00:19:53.450
more than probably
like 50 to 100 feet

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:56.140
away from a source of caffeine.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:19:58.700
That seems to be a theme here.

00:19:58.700 --> 00:20:00.830
And there's a lot of
coffee being drunk here.

00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:02.000
So I get it.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.270
Caffeine is the most abused
substance in the world,

00:20:05.270 --> 00:20:08.012
and it's the most used
substance in the world, which

00:20:08.012 --> 00:20:08.970
is kind of interesting.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:10.636
But did you know that
there are actually

00:20:10.636 --> 00:20:12.440
times, where you can
drink your caffeine,

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:15.320
and it will actually
give you more energy?

00:20:15.320 --> 00:20:17.117
That's probably pretty
interesting to you.

00:20:17.117 --> 00:20:19.200
So it's all based on a
couple of different things.

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:20.990
One is what's called
your cortisol rhythm.

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:24.110
So cortisol is the
fight or flight hormone.

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:26.960
That's the thing that if you're
in trouble, it kicks in gear

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:28.790
and helps you get out of there.

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:32.090
Well, it's also the hormone
that helps pull your body out

00:20:32.090 --> 00:20:33.792
of a state of unconsciousness.

00:20:33.792 --> 00:20:35.250
So when you wake
up in the morning,

00:20:35.250 --> 00:20:37.130
your cortisol levels
are actually quite high.

00:20:37.130 --> 00:20:39.630
When you go to sleep at night,
you want your cortisol levels

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:40.820
to be quite low.

00:20:40.820 --> 00:20:42.830
So thinking about
that for a second,

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:44.600
if our cortisol
level is high, and we

00:20:44.600 --> 00:20:48.530
look at how powerful cortisol
is versus caffeine, what we now

00:20:48.530 --> 00:20:52.160
discover is that
cortisol is like cocaine,

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:54.950
and caffeine is like weak tea.

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:58.460
So it really does almost
no good to add caffeine

00:20:58.460 --> 00:21:01.730
on top of an already elevated
system that's full of cortisol.

00:21:01.730 --> 00:21:07.940
However, if you wait
approximately 90 to 120 minutes

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:11.480
after you wake up, your natural
cortisol level begins to dip.

00:21:11.480 --> 00:21:13.340
And that's when, if
you have caffeine,

00:21:13.340 --> 00:21:16.040
it actually helps elevate
that cortisol level back up

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:17.750
and give you that
level of energy.

00:21:17.750 --> 00:21:20.420
Previously-- so by raise of
hands, how many people in here

00:21:20.420 --> 00:21:22.294
have coffee in the
morning as the first thing

00:21:22.294 --> 00:21:23.660
that they drink?

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:26.210
So that's bad.

00:21:26.210 --> 00:21:27.500
OK, let me tell you why.

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:30.110
When you're at sleep at
night, in your breath,

00:21:30.110 --> 00:21:32.840
you actually breathe
out almost a full liter

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:34.220
of water every night.

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:36.020
And so you wake up dehydrated.

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:39.230
Caffeine is a diuretic,
so when you drink coffee,

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:41.731
all you're doing is actually
not adding fluid to the system.

00:21:41.731 --> 00:21:43.730
You're actually making
it worse, and your system

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:45.950
wants to actually get
rid of even more water.

00:21:45.950 --> 00:21:47.658
Very first thing that
you should be doing

00:21:47.658 --> 00:21:49.970
is drinking a 12 to
16-ounce bottle of water.

00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:52.910
If you can, make it not
cold, but lukewarm, something

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:54.710
that was probably by
your bedside at night.

00:21:54.710 --> 00:21:57.291
But you want to rehydrate
the system, number one.

00:21:57.291 --> 00:21:58.790
Caffeine doesn't
help you with that.

00:21:58.790 --> 00:22:01.514
But waiting 90 to
120 minutes later,

00:22:01.514 --> 00:22:02.930
it actually works
out pretty well.

00:22:02.930 --> 00:22:05.210
The second thing has to do
with your metabolic rhythm.

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:09.152
So caffeine has a half life of
between six and eight hours,

00:22:09.152 --> 00:22:11.360
and so when you're talking
about something like that,

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:14.131
you want to stop caffeine
by about 2:30, 3:00.

00:22:14.131 --> 00:22:16.130
Otherwise, it can have
an effect on your ability

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:19.225
to fall asleep or get into
deeper stages of sleep.

00:22:19.225 --> 00:22:21.350
So I'm sure that there are
plenty of people in here

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:24.440
who will tell me, Michael,
I could have a cup of coffee

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:26.267
at 10:00 at night--

00:22:26.267 --> 00:22:28.100
I've got a couple of
people in the front row

00:22:28.100 --> 00:22:29.690
here that are smiling--

00:22:29.690 --> 00:22:33.050
and I could fall right
asleep, no problem.

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:35.270
That's true, but
that probably means

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:39.260
that you're sleep deprived,
incredibly sleep deprived,

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:40.760
depending upon the
level of caffeine

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:42.020
that you could be bringing in.

00:22:42.020 --> 00:22:44.060
So one of the things
I could say to you

00:22:44.060 --> 00:22:46.052
is if I put something
on your brain

00:22:46.052 --> 00:22:48.260
to monitor your brain waves
as you're falling asleep,

00:22:48.260 --> 00:22:50.180
what I could probably
show you is because you've

00:22:50.180 --> 00:22:52.520
got so much caffeine onboard,
you're actually not getting

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:54.561
into the deeper stages of
sleep, and that's where

00:22:54.561 --> 00:22:56.490
it can become very problematic.

00:22:56.490 --> 00:22:58.250
So the worst thing in
the world you can do

00:22:58.250 --> 00:22:59.541
is drink coffee in the morning.

00:22:59.541 --> 00:23:03.440
So for my chronotypes, this
actually works out really well.

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:05.180
So this is our
first test is trying

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:08.150
to figure out when should each
of these people have caffeine.

00:23:08.150 --> 00:23:10.112
So dolphins will probably
want to have it--

00:23:10.112 --> 00:23:12.320
and I had a couple of dolphins
here in the audience--

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:15.620
probably at 8:30 to 10:00,
and then you can have it again

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:16.910
between 1:00 and 2:00.

00:23:16.910 --> 00:23:19.490
Lions are going to be a little
bit earlier, because remember,

00:23:19.490 --> 00:23:21.740
lions have a tendency to
wake up early in the morning.

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:23.480
Bears-- a little bit later.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:25.190
And then wolves, really--

00:23:25.190 --> 00:23:27.140
and this is a
problem for us wolves

00:23:27.140 --> 00:23:29.030
is because we're so
tired in the mornings,

00:23:29.030 --> 00:23:31.310
and society makes
us get up earlier,

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:34.250
we're just pounding
coffee constantly.

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:36.500
And what you'll find is that
all you're really getting

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:37.370
is side effects from it.

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:38.780
You're really not
getting the energy boost

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:39.779
that you're looking for.

00:23:39.779 --> 00:23:42.650
So I ask wolves to actually have
caffeine much later in the day,

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:44.684
but not too late,
because that's really

00:23:44.684 --> 00:23:46.850
when your energy systems
are going to be kicking in.

00:23:46.850 --> 00:23:49.400
And then you really actually
don't need it as much.

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:51.830
So I'm going to give
everybody a bonus hack,

00:23:51.830 --> 00:23:54.410
and I call this the Nap-a-Latte.

00:23:54.410 --> 00:23:59.637
So let's say that you only got
4 and 1/2 to 5 hours of sleep

00:23:59.637 --> 00:24:01.970
the other night, and you got
a big presentation to give.

00:24:01.970 --> 00:24:03.594
You got something
else that's going on,

00:24:03.594 --> 00:24:05.810
and you've really got
to be on your mark.

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:09.650
So here's what I want you to do
is take a six-ounce cup of drip

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:12.140
coffee, which has the highest
caffeine content, about 100,

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:13.430
110 milligrams.

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:16.670
Put in three ice
cubes to cool it down.

00:24:16.670 --> 00:24:18.860
Slug the whole
thing really quick,

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:21.800
and then take a 25-minute nap.

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:24.132
You'll reduce the amount
of adenosine in your system

00:24:24.132 --> 00:24:25.340
so that you're not as sleepy.

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:27.987
The caffeine locks into
those receptor sites.

00:24:27.987 --> 00:24:29.570
You're good for four
hours guaranteed.

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:31.250
JOE: I do this about
three times a week.

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:33.770
MICHAEL BREUS: So Joe here
has commented that he does

00:24:33.770 --> 00:24:35.280
this about three times a week.

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:36.960
And it really works.

00:24:36.960 --> 00:24:38.210
It's really pretty impressive.

00:24:38.210 --> 00:24:40.790
I use this with all
my Fortune 100 CEOs.

00:24:40.790 --> 00:24:42.650
I use it for whole
executive teams.

00:24:42.650 --> 00:24:44.480
Three times a week
is about the maximum

00:24:44.480 --> 00:24:45.660
that you want to use it.

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:48.860
You don't want to be
using it every day, Joe.

00:24:48.860 --> 00:24:51.530
But it's true, and it works
really, really well, especially

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:53.904
on those days where you really
haven't gotten the quality

00:24:53.904 --> 00:24:56.300
sleep that you were looking for.

00:24:56.300 --> 00:24:58.239
Also, it turns out
broccoli is one

00:24:58.239 --> 00:25:00.530
of the things that will
actually help pull caffeine out

00:25:00.530 --> 00:25:01.070
of your system.

00:25:01.070 --> 00:25:02.540
I've seen two
studies to show this.

00:25:02.540 --> 00:25:05.040
I don't know exactly what the
mechanism of action is there,

00:25:05.040 --> 00:25:06.740
but it turns out that if
you've got too much caffeine

00:25:06.740 --> 00:25:08.510
in your system, steamed
broccoli with dinner

00:25:08.510 --> 00:25:10.510
can actually help pull
some of that caffeine out

00:25:10.510 --> 00:25:12.315
of your system rather quickly.

00:25:12.315 --> 00:25:13.940
So is there a right
time to go running?

00:25:13.940 --> 00:25:15.140
How many people in
here are runners?

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:16.010
I know Nick's a runner.

00:25:16.010 --> 00:25:17.930
OK, so we've got quite a few
people in here are runners.

00:25:17.930 --> 00:25:19.160
So this is very interesting.

00:25:19.160 --> 00:25:21.326
There are different rhythms
in the body that tell us

00:25:21.326 --> 00:25:22.700
when is a good time to run.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:25.410
So it depends on what you want
to accomplish with your run.

00:25:25.410 --> 00:25:27.320
So if you want to
burn fat, you actually

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:29.660
want to run more in the
morning on an empty stomach--

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:32.469
not a dehydrated stomach,
but an empty stomach,

00:25:32.469 --> 00:25:34.760
because your body's got to
get the fuel from someplace,

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:36.680
and so it's going
to pull it from fat.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:40.310
But what if you're a
performance-based runner?

00:25:40.310 --> 00:25:43.220
Like what if you're training
for a marathon or CrossFit,

00:25:43.220 --> 00:25:45.800
or you're doing a triathlon
or something like that?

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:47.990
It turns out that there
are better times of day

00:25:47.990 --> 00:25:50.809
for performance than
you might expect.

00:25:50.809 --> 00:25:52.600
And these are actually
based on chronotype.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:54.530
So lions are actually
best in the late morning,

00:25:54.530 --> 00:25:56.510
which would make sense, because
they're early morning people.

00:25:56.510 --> 00:25:57.500
Bears in the afternoon.

00:25:57.500 --> 00:26:00.080
Wolves are best in the evenings,
and dolphins are actually

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:02.930
good in the morning, because
dolphins use exercise

00:26:02.930 --> 00:26:05.930
to help relax them and
help kind of give them--

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:08.390
take that level of
anxiety and lower it down,

00:26:08.390 --> 00:26:10.850
although one thing I have
noticed about my bears

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:14.510
in general is if bears don't
exercise in the morning,

00:26:14.510 --> 00:26:16.250
they just won't do it.

00:26:16.250 --> 00:26:18.380
So it's pretty interesting.

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:20.720
They might do better
in the later afternoon,

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:23.205
but I promise you that 9
times out of 10, they're

00:26:23.205 --> 00:26:25.580
not going to do it if they
don't exercise in the morning.

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:28.460
So I'd rather you exercise
in the morning, so maybe

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:30.530
as a bear, you might burn
a little bit more fat

00:26:30.530 --> 00:26:33.380
than you might from a
performance standpoint.

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:34.980
But what about
training for strength?

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:37.015
So we talked about cardio, but
what about strength training?

00:26:37.015 --> 00:26:38.850
So strength training
is very interesting.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:41.630
So when you look at the
muscle growth rhythms that

00:26:41.630 --> 00:26:43.590
are out there, it
doesn't really matter

00:26:43.590 --> 00:26:46.220
when you train if you want
your muscles to get bigger.

00:26:46.220 --> 00:26:49.490
But if you want them to
actually get stronger,

00:26:49.490 --> 00:26:51.450
there actually is
a rhythm based on--

00:26:51.450 --> 00:26:52.370
God bless you.

00:26:52.370 --> 00:26:54.050
Actually, God bless all of us--

00:26:54.050 --> 00:26:56.981
based on-- that got the
biggest laugh so far.

00:26:56.981 --> 00:26:57.480
All right.

00:26:57.480 --> 00:26:58.170
Good to know.

00:26:58.170 --> 00:27:02.000
So he timed that just
perfectly for me.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:03.650
So when you look
at muscle strength,

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:06.530
it turns out that there are--

00:27:06.530 --> 00:27:08.790
it's a testosterone ratio.

00:27:08.790 --> 00:27:10.700
And so when we have
more testosterone,

00:27:10.700 --> 00:27:12.320
we actually can have
better strength.

00:27:12.320 --> 00:27:15.212
And so looking at lions, bears,
and dolphins, and wolves,

00:27:15.212 --> 00:27:17.420
we actually know what their
testosterone rhythms are.

00:27:17.420 --> 00:27:19.610
And that's part of the
reason why they can actually

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:22.160
lift more weights
and actually be

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:25.760
stronger by doing their
exercise at different times.

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:27.110
So we've talked about caffeine.

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:29.150
We've talked about exercise.

