Sometimes they have
something else going on.

00:39:42.210 --> 00:39:45.030
But my dolphins-- and you notice
how early these times are.

00:39:45.030 --> 00:39:47.250
So for my lions,
4:00 AM to 6:00 AM.

00:39:47.250 --> 00:39:49.170
Well, hopefully, you're
not awake at 4:00 AM.

00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:50.920
That's kind of where
the REM is coming in.

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:53.350
But right after you wake
up, one of the best ways

00:39:53.350 --> 00:39:55.450
to do something is take
a topic, and put it

00:39:55.450 --> 00:39:57.610
on a piece of paper and
a pen, and then put it

00:39:57.610 --> 00:39:58.662
by your bedside.

00:39:58.662 --> 00:40:01.120
And when you wake up in the
morning, the first thing you do

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:02.620
is look at that
topic and write down

00:40:02.620 --> 00:40:04.780
everything you can think
about about that topic.

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:06.820
Within five to seven
days, I guarantee you,

00:40:06.820 --> 00:40:09.291
you will come up with an idea
that you've never had before.

00:40:09.291 --> 00:40:11.290
Again, it's because of
this microprocessing that

00:40:11.290 --> 00:40:12.520
gets to go on in your head.

00:40:12.520 --> 00:40:13.728
And that's not the only time.

00:40:13.728 --> 00:40:15.850
The second time happens
to be in the afternoon.

00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:18.547
Now if you notice here,
Dolphins between 2:00 and 4:00,

00:40:18.547 --> 00:40:20.380
and I'm talking over
here that you shouldn't

00:40:20.380 --> 00:40:22.240
go between 11:00 and 3:00.

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:25.060
Dolphins are different,
because their level of anxiety

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:25.750
is much higher.

00:40:25.750 --> 00:40:28.870
And so they can actually funnel
in and get to that moment

00:40:28.870 --> 00:40:31.420
a little bit earlier
when most of us can't.

00:40:31.420 --> 00:40:33.670
But again, what I did
was I lined up the times,

00:40:33.670 --> 00:40:35.620
and so you actually
have two times of day

00:40:35.620 --> 00:40:38.350
where brainstorming is going to
be better than any other time

00:40:38.350 --> 00:40:39.130
during the day.

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:40.730
Now how many people in
here by a raise of hands

00:40:40.730 --> 00:40:42.938
have ever noticed that there
are certain times of day

00:40:42.938 --> 00:40:45.280
that they do things
better than others?

00:40:45.280 --> 00:40:47.110
So this is what I'm
talking about here

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:49.510
is if you're trying
to force a brainstorm,

00:40:49.510 --> 00:40:50.620
it doesn't always work.

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:53.680
But if you know what times
you're able to naturally get

00:40:53.680 --> 00:40:55.690
there, give yourself a shot.

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.120
You might be surprised
at what happens.

00:40:58.120 --> 00:41:01.480
The same holds true for
being on in terms of being

00:41:01.480 --> 00:41:03.550
able to be alert and focused.

00:41:03.550 --> 00:41:06.806
So I'm sure a lot of you have
to present ideas to people

00:41:06.806 --> 00:41:08.680
and be able to talk to
people and tell people

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:09.880
all the kinds of things
that you're working on

00:41:09.880 --> 00:41:10.900
and things like that.

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:13.360
Well, it turns out that there
are certain chronotypes that

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:14.540
do this better than others.

00:41:14.540 --> 00:41:17.590
Lions, they love to
be in front of a room.

00:41:17.590 --> 00:41:19.240
Not a big surprise.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:21.640
My COO is my kind of
leaders of the pack.

00:41:21.640 --> 00:41:23.050
Not a big shocker there.

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:24.480
Dolphins-- not as much.

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:26.230
They can do it, but
they would much rather

00:41:26.230 --> 00:41:29.080
be in the back and kind of being
able to do their own thing.

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:31.704
Wolves would actually prefer
to go to happy hour as opposed

00:41:31.704 --> 00:41:34.120
to give a major presentation,
which is what I would prefer

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:35.127
to do most of the time.

00:41:35.127 --> 00:41:37.210
And bears are actually
happy to be in the audience

00:41:37.210 --> 00:41:40.000
and learn from the presentation,
not necessarily have

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:41.890
to give that presentation.

00:41:41.890 --> 00:41:45.040
But there are actually rhythms
for attending a presentation.

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:46.990
So let's say you want
to schedule a time,

00:41:46.990 --> 00:41:50.470
so actually, the most flexible
time is between 2:30 and 3:00

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:51.850
in the afternoon.

00:41:51.850 --> 00:41:54.010
The second best time is
between 10:00 and 11:00,

00:41:54.010 --> 00:41:55.954
so not when somebody
just gets there,

00:41:55.954 --> 00:41:58.120
but after they've had a
chance to kind of settle in.

00:41:58.120 --> 00:42:01.600
The least flexible time, as
you can see, 9:15, worst time.

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:03.070
Second worst time
is 12:00 to 1:00.

00:42:03.070 --> 00:42:05.980
So these are data that come
from a-- there was a software

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:07.630
program called Meet with Me.

00:42:07.630 --> 00:42:10.219
And they had over half
a million meetings,

00:42:10.219 --> 00:42:12.760
and then you had to click that
you were attending the meeting

00:42:12.760 --> 00:42:14.110
or not attending the meeting.

00:42:14.110 --> 00:42:19.060
And so these data actually are
full on, straight up objective.

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:21.826
Turns out Tuesday afternoons
have the highest flexibility

00:42:21.826 --> 00:42:23.200
for meetings, and
Monday mornings

00:42:23.200 --> 00:42:25.210
have the lowest flexibility.

00:42:25.210 --> 00:42:26.530
Not really a big surprise.

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:30.790
Who wants to have an 8:00 AM,
Monday morning meeting, right?

00:42:30.790 --> 00:42:31.990
Nobody.

00:42:31.990 --> 00:42:33.055
Nobody wants to do that.

00:42:33.055 --> 00:42:34.930
And also, it's really
hard to start your week

00:42:34.930 --> 00:42:37.330
off having that kind of
meeting and things like that.

00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:40.450
Now aside from assigning
when the presentation be, how

00:42:40.450 --> 00:42:41.762
about giving the presentation?

00:42:41.762 --> 00:42:43.720
So you want to have your
energy rhythm, so when

00:42:43.720 --> 00:42:45.402
are you at your peak?

00:42:45.402 --> 00:42:47.110
When are you going to
be most articulate?

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:48.310
When are you going to be
able to focus the most

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:49.779
and give the most information?

00:42:49.779 --> 00:42:51.820
And then engagement-- when
is your audience going

00:42:51.820 --> 00:42:54.250
to have an interest in
what you're having to say?

00:42:54.250 --> 00:42:57.310
So I actually created,
again, another matrix

00:42:57.310 --> 00:42:58.750
based on chronotypes.

00:42:58.750 --> 00:43:00.850
And what you'll find is
that different people

00:43:00.850 --> 00:43:02.990
are on at different times.

00:43:02.990 --> 00:43:05.410
This is why when I
chronotype a company,

00:43:05.410 --> 00:43:07.172
it gets really interesting
really quickly,

00:43:07.172 --> 00:43:09.130
because we've got the
presenter, and then we've

00:43:09.130 --> 00:43:09.838
got the audience.

00:43:09.838 --> 00:43:12.130
And making that
match appropriately

00:43:12.130 --> 00:43:14.290
turns out to be a
really interesting way

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:17.155
to increase levels
of productivity.

00:43:17.155 --> 00:43:18.530
A couple of things
about audience

00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:20.154
engagement that you
may know or may not

00:43:20.154 --> 00:43:22.970
know-- roughly 30 minutes after
you start, one in seven people

00:43:22.970 --> 00:43:23.720
will be zoned out.

00:43:23.720 --> 00:43:26.630
I can see people already
starting to get there.

00:43:26.630 --> 00:43:29.960
After 45 minutes, one in three
will basically become a zombie.

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:32.000
And then you do have
something that's

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.900
called cognitive
backlog that occurs.

00:43:34.900 --> 00:43:36.776
So right now, I've
given you-- you're

00:43:36.776 --> 00:43:38.150
like drinking from
the fire hose.

00:43:38.150 --> 00:43:40.580
I've given you so
much information.

00:43:40.580 --> 00:43:41.930
Don't expect to remember it all.

00:43:41.930 --> 00:43:43.084
Check out the book.

00:43:43.084 --> 00:43:44.750
Don't forget that
this is all being live

00:43:44.750 --> 00:43:47.041
streamed, and it's going to
be up on YouTube for people

00:43:47.041 --> 00:43:47.569
to watch.

00:43:47.569 --> 00:43:48.860
So don't try to take it all in.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:51.980
But you can't get that much
information in your brain

00:43:51.980 --> 00:43:54.260
at any one given time.

00:43:54.260 --> 00:43:55.940
Best and worst
times to present--

00:43:55.940 --> 00:43:57.830
this is, again,
based on energy level

00:43:57.830 --> 00:44:00.740
for my different
chronotypes and worst times

00:44:00.740 --> 00:44:02.520
for everybody in general.

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:04.860
So even if you don't know
everybody in your audience,

00:44:04.860 --> 00:44:06.950
these are the times
that you want to avoid,

00:44:06.950 --> 00:44:09.150
if you possibly can.

00:44:09.150 --> 00:44:11.480
So what about making a decision?

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:14.150
So it turns out that there are
on peak times, where you're

00:44:14.150 --> 00:44:16.820
logical, very low risk
in your decision making,

00:44:16.820 --> 00:44:19.100
and off peak times, where
you're far more emotional

00:44:19.100 --> 00:44:21.146
and high risk decision making.

00:44:21.146 --> 00:44:23.270
These are actually influenced
by sleep deprivation,

00:44:23.270 --> 00:44:25.850
your personality, and what
we call the procrastination

00:44:25.850 --> 00:44:26.690
rhythm.

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:27.950
So everybody in here's
probably familiar with

00:44:27.950 --> 00:44:29.120
the procrastination rhythm.

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.250
It turns out that this is
actually by chronotype,

00:44:31.250 --> 00:44:34.700
and so some of my chronotypes
are world champion

00:44:34.700 --> 00:44:36.320
procrastinators--

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:40.056
those would be the wolves or the
late night people like myself.

00:44:40.056 --> 00:44:41.930
The people who are not
big on procrastination

00:44:41.930 --> 00:44:44.760
turns out to be the lions
and the early morning people.

00:44:44.760 --> 00:44:46.500
It's kind of interesting.

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:48.870
So when is the best time
for you to make a decision?

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:51.286
So these are the times during
the day that you're actually

00:44:51.286 --> 00:44:54.170
going to make the most
clear-headed logical decision

00:44:54.170 --> 00:44:57.860
based on your endocrine system,
based on when your hormones are

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:00.776
hitting the different highs and
lows throughout the day, which,

00:45:00.776 --> 00:45:02.150
again, is pretty
interesting when

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:03.316
you start to think about it.

00:45:03.316 --> 00:45:04.370
Could I reschedule?

00:45:04.370 --> 00:45:06.410
Could I rejigger my
schedule one way or another

00:45:06.410 --> 00:45:08.710
to be able to allow me
to make better decisions,

00:45:08.710 --> 00:45:11.150
to be able to be more
productive, things like that?

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.780
So can you hack your chronotype?

00:45:14.780 --> 00:45:16.400
So the answer is yes, you can.

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:19.340
I'm not sure you
want to, but you can.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:22.520
So the strategic use of
light, caffeine, and melatonin

00:45:22.520 --> 00:45:25.130
can do this, because here's
the thing to remember

00:45:25.130 --> 00:45:28.220
is if you're a wolf, and you're
living in a bear's world,

00:45:28.220 --> 00:45:30.424
all you are is jet lagged.

00:45:30.424 --> 00:45:32.090
And these are the
components that we use

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:33.770
to help people with jet lag.

00:45:33.770 --> 00:45:37.700
So if you want to, you can
actually utilize light therapy.

00:45:37.700 --> 00:45:40.250
I know we had Fred Maxik
talking earlier this week

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:41.864
about how to use light.

00:45:41.864 --> 00:45:44.030
And you can have melatonin
in the evenings, caffeine

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:46.040
and light in the mornings,
and you can actually

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:47.346
shift yourself.

00:45:47.346 --> 00:45:49.220
You can actually make
yourself into something

00:45:49.220 --> 00:45:52.100
that you weren't genetically
predisposed to be.

00:45:52.100 --> 00:45:54.665
I don't recommend it,
but it is something

00:45:54.665 --> 00:45:56.540
that, unfortunately,
some of us have to do it

00:45:56.540 --> 00:45:58.400
whether we like it or not.

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:00.050
And so thinking
through these ideas,

00:46:00.050 --> 00:46:02.300
you don't necessarily want
to go against your genetics

00:46:02.300 --> 00:46:04.580
if you can possibly help it.

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:06.330
How do you make yourself
a morning person?

00:46:06.330 --> 00:46:07.788
This is the second
biggest question

00:46:07.788 --> 00:46:10.880
I get after sex is,
how do I change myself

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:12.500
to become that morning person?

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:15.080
So here's a couple of ideas
that you can try, if you'd like,

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:15.759
at home.

00:46:15.759 --> 00:46:18.050
So first of all, going to
bed at the right time for you

00:46:18.050 --> 00:46:19.760
every night-- again,
it's in the book,

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:21.920
but it's also based
on your chronotype.

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:24.642
Number two, never hit
the snooze button.

00:46:24.642 --> 00:46:26.600
So by a raise of hands,
how many people in here

00:46:26.600 --> 00:46:29.161
hit the snooze
button at least once?

00:46:29.161 --> 00:46:29.660
Come on.

00:46:29.660 --> 00:46:30.200
Don't lie.

00:46:30.200 --> 00:46:31.280
OK, keep your hands raised.

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:32.238
Keep your hands raised.

00:46:32.238 --> 00:46:33.710
Twice?

00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:35.640
Three times?

00:46:35.640 --> 00:46:36.840
Four times?

00:46:36.840 --> 00:46:37.340
All right.

00:46:37.340 --> 00:46:38.240
So we ended at three.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:39.739
I was giving this
lecture, and I had

00:46:39.739 --> 00:46:43.079
somebody at seven times
for a snooze button.

00:46:43.079 --> 00:46:44.870
So let me tell you why
the snooze button is

00:46:44.870 --> 00:46:46.966
the single worst
invention in all of sleep.

00:46:46.966 --> 00:46:48.590
So it turns out that
the average snooze

00:46:48.590 --> 00:46:50.870
is between seven and
nine minutes long,

00:46:50.870 --> 00:46:54.530
and your body physically can't
get into a deep stage of sleep

00:46:54.530 --> 00:46:55.140
at that point.

00:46:55.140 --> 00:46:58.340
And we know that REM sleep--
remember from the creativity

00:46:58.340 --> 00:47:00.710
stuff and the
brainstorming stuff--

00:47:00.710 --> 00:47:03.110
the bulk of it happens in
the last part of the night.

00:47:03.110 --> 00:47:04.700
So what you do by
hitting the snooze

00:47:04.700 --> 00:47:07.310
is you actually knock down
your levels of creativity

00:47:07.310 --> 00:47:08.356
and brainstorming.

00:47:08.356 --> 00:47:09.980
I'd much rather you
just set your alarm

00:47:09.980 --> 00:47:11.521
for the last possible
moment that you

00:47:11.521 --> 00:47:14.300
have to wake up, because you'll
get a lot more better quality

00:47:14.300 --> 00:47:15.637
sleep.

00:47:15.637 --> 00:47:17.720
Get direct sunlight for
10 minutes in the morning.

00:47:17.720 --> 00:47:18.980
So once you've reached
over, and you've

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:21.650
grabbed your bottle of water,
because you're dehydrated,

00:47:21.650 --> 00:47:24.530
I want you to walk to the
window and get some sunlight.

00:47:24.530 --> 00:47:25.370
Do me a favor.

00:47:25.370 --> 00:47:26.820
Put on a robe.

00:47:26.820 --> 00:47:28.070
I have to tell this to people.

00:47:28.070 --> 00:47:29.736
Lots of time, they
don't think about it,

00:47:29.736 --> 00:47:32.180
and then the neighbors
get a big scare.

00:47:32.180 --> 00:47:34.130
Remember to drink
your water, and let

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:36.020
there be light and music.

00:47:36.020 --> 00:47:37.400
So it's very, very interesting.

00:47:37.400 --> 00:47:39.110
How many people listen
to music in the mornings

00:47:39.110 --> 00:47:40.235
when they're getting ready?

00:47:40.235 --> 00:47:42.960
So that's a great thing that
you do, and it works really,

00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:43.460
really well.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:47.060
And you should use high
energy, high emotion music,

00:47:47.060 --> 00:47:50.530
so music that you love to dance
to that really gets you going

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:53.285
is fantastic, because then
you're using a secondary sense.

00:47:53.285 --> 00:47:55.160
You're not just having
light, but you're also

00:47:55.160 --> 00:47:58.140
having sound to help wake
your brain up in the morning.

00:47:58.140 --> 00:47:59.540
So one of the things that--

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:03.195
so in our house, my son
listens to music almost

00:48:03.195 --> 00:48:04.070
every single morning.

00:48:04.070 --> 00:48:05.870
My daughter doesn't
necessarily like it,

00:48:05.870 --> 00:48:07.666
and when it's too
early in the morning,

00:48:07.666 --> 00:48:10.040
because she can sleep in a
little bit longer than he can.

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:12.140
And so the rule in
our house is at 6:30

00:48:12.140 --> 00:48:15.350
is when you can actually
fire up the music.

00:48:15.350 --> 00:48:19.220
And I walk in there, and he's
singing, he's dancing around,

00:48:19.220 --> 00:48:21.200
and he's 15 years old.

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:24.590
To get a 15-year-old to get
up at 6:30 in the morning

00:48:24.590 --> 00:48:27.200
and be any level
of consciousness

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:29.070
is almost an impossibility.

00:48:29.070 --> 00:48:31.370
So by having that
light that's coming in,

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:33.230
and then also having
the music, it really

00:48:33.230 --> 00:48:35.330
has a tendency to help you out.

00:48:35.330 --> 00:48:37.040
Exercising your body
and mind is always

00:48:37.040 --> 00:48:40.070
going to be good, even if you
can only do 10 pushups or 15

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:41.450
pushups in the morning.

00:48:41.450 --> 00:48:43.957
Do something to get
your heart rate up.

00:48:43.957 --> 00:48:46.040
If it's dancing around,
don't dance in the shower.

00:48:46.040 --> 00:48:47.230
Dance outside of the shower.

00:48:47.230 --> 00:48:48.750
We don't want anybody
slipping and falling,

00:48:48.750 --> 00:48:50.500
but at the end of the
day, doing something

00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:52.184
to get that level of
energy up is good.

00:48:52.184 --> 00:48:54.600
If it's Saturday morning,
that's the perfect time for sex,

00:48:54.600 --> 00:48:55.670
so go ahead and try that.

00:48:55.670 --> 00:48:56.295
You never know.

00:48:56.295 --> 00:48:58.800
It might help wake you up and
make you a morning person.

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:00.300
The other thing I
want to talk about

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:03.140
is a cool, not cold shower.

00:49:03.140 --> 00:49:06.050
So this is something that I do
every morning or most mornings,

00:49:06.050 --> 00:49:08.077
and it's a meditation
technique that I do.

00:49:08.077 --> 00:49:09.660
And I teach it to
people all the time.

00:49:09.660 --> 00:49:11.870
So you stand in front,
where the showerhead

00:49:11.870 --> 00:49:13.340
is right at your
head, and you have

00:49:13.340 --> 00:49:15.800
it hit you literally
square between the eyes.

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:18.290
There's like a waterfall
of water that comes down,

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:20.990
and it covers your nose, so it's
actually difficult to breathe.

00:49:20.990 --> 00:49:22.640
So you have to
open up your mouth,

00:49:22.640 --> 00:49:25.654
and you have to concentrate
really hard on how you breathe.

00:49:25.654 --> 00:49:27.320
And if you sit there
for about a minute,

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:31.370
you can't think of anything
other than your breathing.

00:49:31.370 --> 00:49:34.460
And so it really focuses you in,
and you really come out of this

00:49:34.460 --> 00:49:35.930
really in the moment.

00:49:35.930 --> 00:49:38.864
While you're doing
that, take the nozzle,

00:49:38.864 --> 00:49:41.030
and turn it to get a little
cooler, a little cooler,

00:49:41.030 --> 00:49:41.696
a little cooler.

00:49:41.696 --> 00:49:42.969
Don't make it cold.

00:49:42.969 --> 00:49:43.760
Just get it cooler.

00:49:43.760 --> 00:49:47.500
What happens is the blood
shunts into your trunk,

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:49.500
and it actually causes
your heart rate to go up,

00:49:49.500 --> 00:49:51.230
and it actually helps
wake you up even more.

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:53.570
So by using this meditation,
and then when you turn off

00:49:53.570 --> 00:49:54.920
the shower, you are bam.

00:49:54.920 --> 00:49:56.150
You are in the now.

00:49:56.150 --> 00:49:58.970
That's a great time for
journaling and for creativity

00:49:58.970 --> 00:50:00.920
or just getting your day going.

00:50:00.920 --> 00:50:04.010
And then start your day
with a fairly decent-sized

00:50:04.010 --> 00:50:05.960
protein-rich breakfast.

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:08.850
Protein and good fat is going
to be much better for you.

00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:11.930
I was actually able to come
around to some of the cafes

00:50:11.930 --> 00:50:14.330
here, and they've got some
fantastic options here

00:50:14.330 --> 00:50:16.621
at Google for you to be able
to do something like that.

00:50:16.621 --> 00:50:18.570
You want to avoid
carbs in the morning,

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:20.150
even though they
taste really good.

00:50:20.150 --> 00:50:22.700
There's a lot of data to show
that carbs make you sleepy.

00:50:22.700 --> 00:50:25.630
And so if you're a wolf, and
you don't do well at mornings

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:27.980
anyway, a bagel is
about the worst thing

00:50:27.980 --> 00:50:29.870
that you could possibly
put into your body,

00:50:29.870 --> 00:50:32.510
because all your body wants to
do after something like that

00:50:32.510 --> 00:50:33.350
is sleep.

00:50:33.350 --> 00:50:37.050
And so with that, I will
open it up for questions.

00:50:37.050 --> 00:50:38.780
You can ask me
questions about timing.

00:50:38.780 --> 00:50:41.834
You can ask me questions about
sleep, whatever you want.

00:50:41.834 --> 00:50:43.250
AUDIENCE: You were
just mentioning

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:46.910
about some protein-rich
breakfast options,

00:50:46.910 --> 00:50:48.320
and what would those be?

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:49.250
MICHAEL BREUS: So
if I was looking

00:50:49.250 --> 00:50:51.583
for a protein-rich breakfast,
I might consider something

00:50:51.583 --> 00:50:54.350
like an omelet with avocado
would be a great option,

00:50:54.350 --> 00:50:56.540
because you get the good
fat from the avocado,

00:50:56.540 --> 00:50:58.580
and you get the
protein from the eggs.

00:50:58.580 --> 00:51:00.770
A lot of people-- for
example, a lot of my people

00:51:00.770 --> 00:51:02.570
who are night
people like wolves,

00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:04.460
they have almost no
appetite in the morning.

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:07.760
So for those people, a protein
shake or a protein smoothie

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:09.260
would actually work
out pretty well.

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:10.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I hate
eating in the morning.

00:51:10.820 --> 00:51:12.194
MICHAEL BREUS:
Yeah, and so do I.

00:51:12.194 --> 00:51:14.270
And so the only thing I
can literally choke down

00:51:14.270 --> 00:51:16.430
is a smoothie, barely.

00:51:16.430 --> 00:51:17.400
So that's what I do.

00:51:17.400 --> 00:51:19.040
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:20.930
AUDIENCE: Just
curious, is it just

00:51:20.930 --> 00:51:23.840
the genetics 100% that
decides the chronotype,

00:51:23.840 --> 00:51:26.342
or are there any external
factors or social factors?

00:51:26.342 --> 00:51:27.800
MICHAEL BREUS: So
it's the genetics

00:51:27.800 --> 00:51:29.697
that determine the
chronotype, but it's

00:51:29.697 --> 00:51:31.280
the external factors
is whether or not

00:51:31.280 --> 00:51:33.080
you can follow the chronotype.

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:34.830
Also, it changes over time.

00:51:34.830 --> 00:51:36.920
So as an example with
my daughter, she's 13,

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:39.350
so she's going to
be more of a wolf.

00:51:39.350 --> 00:51:42.590
But as she gets older, she
might be more of a bear.

00:51:42.590 --> 00:51:44.629
She might be more of a
lion, things like that.

00:51:44.629 --> 00:51:46.670
We also know that as we
get even older, like when

00:51:46.670 --> 00:51:50.401
we hit senior years like 55,
65, that kind of age range,

00:51:50.401 --> 00:51:52.650
then we also start to see
people go one of two routes.

00:51:52.650 --> 00:51:53.960
They either go in
towards the lion,

00:51:53.960 --> 00:51:56.168
so you see a lot of people
having dinner at 5 o'clock

00:51:56.168 --> 00:51:59.450
and getting up super early,
or they go towards a dolphin,

00:51:59.450 --> 00:52:01.204
because they become
more medically frail.

00:52:01.204 --> 00:52:02.870
There's more medications
on board, which

00:52:02.870 --> 00:52:04.550
can be disruptive to sleep.

00:52:04.550 --> 00:52:06.340
AUDIENCE: You said
that for bears.

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:07.670
afternoon exercise is best.

00:52:07.670 --> 00:52:09.100
But if they don't
exercise in the morning,

00:52:09.100 --> 00:52:10.141
it's not going to happen.

00:52:10.141 --> 00:52:11.880
That's totally me.

00:52:11.880 --> 00:52:14.422
Why is that the case, and how
is it different for the others?

00:52:14.422 --> 00:52:15.838
MICHAEL BREUS: So
it's interesting

00:52:15.838 --> 00:52:17.490
when we look at
exercise in particular,

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:21.410
but there's also a motivation
factor, an adherence

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:22.070
to exercise.

00:52:22.070 --> 00:52:24.230
And so there's some
data to now suggest

00:52:24.230 --> 00:52:28.730
that if you do something
for between 21 and 25 days,

00:52:28.730 --> 00:52:30.140
it becomes a habit.

00:52:30.140 --> 00:52:34.504
And so what I found with my
bears is if they're not willing

00:52:34.504 --> 00:52:36.170
to do it in the
afternoon, which, again,

00:52:36.170 --> 00:52:38.330
is where their strength
rhythm is coming from--

00:52:38.330 --> 00:52:40.760
not necessarily fat
burning, but strength,

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:42.140
not necessarily muscle growth--

00:52:42.140 --> 00:52:44.320
then I can convince
them sometimes at least

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:45.320
to do it in the morning.

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:47.112
And then slowly, I try
to get them to do it

00:52:47.112 --> 00:52:48.778
towards the afternoon,
and they actually

00:52:48.778 --> 00:52:50.630
find that their
performance is better.

00:52:50.630 --> 00:52:52.338
AUDIENCE: What do you
think about napping

00:52:52.338 --> 00:52:54.407
during afternoons in general?

00:52:54.407 --> 00:52:56.240
MICHAEL BREUS: So
generally, I love napping,

00:52:56.240 --> 00:52:57.369
unless you're a dolphin.

00:52:57.369 --> 00:52:59.660
If you're a dolphin, or you
have any level of insomnia,

00:52:59.660 --> 00:53:01.701
napping is about the worst
thing that you can do,

00:53:01.701 --> 00:53:03.487
because it, again,
lowers that sleep drive

00:53:03.487 --> 00:53:04.820
and makes it difficult to sleep.

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:07.220
But a 25-minute nap
works really well,

00:53:07.220 --> 00:53:11.090
and the Nap-a-Latte works
really well, if you try that.

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:13.590
But I'm a big fan of the nap,
but you want to keep it short.

00:53:13.590 --> 00:53:15.900
Anybody here ever take
a nap and feel worse

00:53:15.900 --> 00:53:17.150
when they got up from the nap?

00:53:17.150 --> 00:53:18.590
That means you napped too long.

00:53:18.590 --> 00:53:20.589
So if you're keeping it
to that 25-minute range,

00:53:20.589 --> 00:53:22.680
you only get about some
stage 1 and stage 2 sleep,

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.290
and it makes it
easier to wake up.

00:53:24.290 --> 00:53:25.100
Yes, over here.

00:53:25.100 --> 00:53:27.770
AUDIENCE: So if you had
to do just one thing,

00:53:27.770 --> 00:53:29.210
and you were stuck
between forced

00:53:29.210 --> 00:53:31.370
to get up too early
for a long commute,

00:53:31.370 --> 00:53:33.860
forced to stay up too late just
to keep on top of the house

00:53:33.860 --> 00:53:37.392
and help the kids with homework,
not a lot of options of change

00:53:37.392 --> 00:53:39.350
schedules, so it's really
overconstrained like,

00:53:39.350 --> 00:53:41.870
I think, many of us,
what's one first thing you

00:53:41.870 --> 00:53:44.352
do to make it better?

00:53:44.352 --> 00:53:46.310
MICHAEL BREUS: I would
keep your sleep schedule

00:53:46.310 --> 00:53:48.554
the same on the weekends
as during the week,

00:53:48.554 --> 00:53:49.470
because what ends up--

00:53:49.470 --> 00:53:52.356
so you're crunched from
both ends is what you're--

00:53:52.356 --> 00:53:54.230
the description that
you're giving me is I've

00:53:54.230 --> 00:53:56.070
got to stay up late
to get stuff done,

00:53:56.070 --> 00:53:57.320
and then I got to get
up early, because I've

00:53:57.320 --> 00:53:58.640
got a decent sized commute.

00:53:58.640 --> 00:53:59.750
So you've got this here.

00:53:59.750 --> 00:54:01.640
So lots of people
in that scenario

00:54:01.640 --> 00:54:03.349
try to catch up on
sleep on the weekends,

00:54:03.349 --> 00:54:04.764
and what ends up
happening is they

00:54:04.764 --> 00:54:07.070
actually shift their circadian
clock and make it worse.

00:54:07.070 --> 00:54:09.410
So I'd rather you keep your
schedule as consistent.

00:54:09.410 --> 00:54:11.874
So if you wake up at, let's
say, 6:30 during the week,

00:54:11.874 --> 00:54:13.790
I'd ask you to wake up
at 6:30 on the weekends

00:54:13.790 --> 00:54:16.730
as well, which I know
is not a popular idea.

00:54:16.730 --> 00:54:19.430
But what you'll find is you
can fall asleep more quickly,

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:21.500
and you'll be able to
get into deeper sleep

00:54:21.500 --> 00:54:24.710
faster and stay there
longer the more consistent

00:54:24.710 --> 00:54:25.724
your sleep schedule is.

00:54:25.724 --> 00:54:27.140
So that would be
the first thing I

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:31.070
would say is keep your bedtime
and wake time consistent.

00:54:31.070 --> 00:54:33.500
The other thing I would do is
look at your coffee intake,

00:54:33.500 --> 00:54:35.520
and see if you can
tweak that a little bit,

00:54:35.520 --> 00:54:38.020
because if you've got a commute,
and you're riding a vehicle

00:54:38.020 --> 00:54:40.550
or something like that, maybe
carpooling might be better,

00:54:40.550 --> 00:54:42.470
because your reaction
time is definitely

00:54:42.470 --> 00:54:44.360
going to be slower, for sure.

00:54:44.360 --> 00:54:45.996
AUDIENCE: My
question, though, is

00:54:45.996 --> 00:54:47.870
what's the effect size
here on some of these?

00:54:47.870 --> 00:54:50.125
You're seeing better,
and I basically

00:54:50.125 --> 00:54:52.250
want to know how much better
my sex is going to be.

00:54:52.250 --> 00:54:53.300
MICHAEL BREUS: OK, so you
wonder how much better

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:53.990
your sex is going to be.

00:54:53.990 --> 00:54:55.200
So that's a great question.

00:54:55.200 --> 00:54:59.330
So it really looks more at
does-- so in sex in particular,

00:54:59.330 --> 00:55:00.620
it's looking more at desire.

00:55:00.620 --> 00:55:02.030
And so when is desire around?

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:05.135
And so it's hard to
quantify exactly,

00:55:05.135 --> 00:55:07.010
but here's one of the
things I can tell you--

00:55:07.010 --> 00:55:09.380
and it's great that you
chose sex in particular--

00:55:09.380 --> 00:55:11.720
is we know that a
preponderance of men

00:55:11.720 --> 00:55:13.910
wake up with an erection.

00:55:13.910 --> 00:55:15.620
And so if that's
the case, clearly

00:55:15.620 --> 00:55:17.960
mother nature is
saying, this is the time

00:55:17.960 --> 00:55:20.487
that you need to be doing
this particular activity.

00:55:20.487 --> 00:55:22.820
So what I would say is I'm
going to actually put it back

00:55:22.820 --> 00:55:24.861
on to you, and so what
I'm going to ask you to do

00:55:24.861 --> 00:55:26.870
is I want you to run
the experiment for me,

00:55:26.870 --> 00:55:30.202
and then let us know if it's
increased your sex life any

00:55:30.202 --> 00:55:31.910
more or less, and
we'll see what happens.

00:55:31.910 --> 00:55:34.757
But right now, the
data isn't that clear.

00:55:34.757 --> 00:55:37.340
But when we look at these things
and we say things are better,

00:55:37.340 --> 00:55:38.960
what we're finding
is anecdotally,

00:55:38.960 --> 00:55:40.610
a tremendous number
of people are--

00:55:40.610 --> 00:55:44.430
I get hundreds of emails
of people saying, holy cow,

00:55:44.430 --> 00:55:46.340
this really is interesting.

00:55:46.340 --> 00:55:48.530
And I don't want people to
change their whole lives.

00:55:48.530 --> 00:55:51.380
I want them to get their sleep
schedule down, and then just

00:55:51.380 --> 00:55:52.607
pick one thing from the book.

00:55:52.607 --> 00:55:54.440
There are literally 50
different activities.

00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:56.080
Most people look at
the sex part first,

00:55:56.080 --> 00:55:58.360
but if that's what you
want to do, go for it.

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:01.100
But you'll be surprised
at-- it absolutely

00:56:01.100 --> 00:56:02.875
is incrementally better.

00:56:02.875 --> 00:56:05.000
AUDIENCE: What is your
opinion on polyphasic sleep,

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.580
and how does it differ
from adaptive sleep habits?

00:56:07.580 --> 00:56:10.814
For example, habitual napping
at a set time per day.

00:56:10.814 --> 00:56:12.230
MICHAEL BREUS: So
for those of you

00:56:12.230 --> 00:56:14.354
out there that don't know
what polyphasic sleep is,

00:56:14.354 --> 00:56:16.880
so this is an idea, where
you can get your eight

00:56:16.880 --> 00:56:18.931
hours in about four and 1/2.

00:56:18.931 --> 00:56:20.180
So everybody's ears perked up.

00:56:20.180 --> 00:56:21.420
Oh, how do I do that?

00:56:21.420 --> 00:56:24.620
So what you end up doing is you
have a core amount of sleep,

00:56:24.620 --> 00:56:26.960
usually three sleep cycles,
about four and 1/2 hours.

00:56:26.960 --> 00:56:30.170
And then you take
25 to 35-minute naps

00:56:30.170 --> 00:56:32.329
at very particular times
throughout the day,

00:56:32.329 --> 00:56:34.370
and that can be the most
extreme situation, where

00:56:34.370 --> 00:56:36.050
you would actually
reduce total sleep

00:56:36.050 --> 00:56:38.494
time by about 200 minutes.

00:56:38.494 --> 00:56:40.910
Here's the pros and the cons
of doing something like that.

00:56:40.910 --> 00:56:44.210
Yes, you do get more time,
but you don't really.

00:56:44.210 --> 00:56:45.960
So here's what goes
on is, first of all,

00:56:45.960 --> 00:56:48.500
you're awake when almost
everybody out there is asleep.

00:56:48.500 --> 00:56:50.960
So there's only so many things
you can do on the internet

00:56:50.960 --> 00:56:52.751
to talk to somebody in
a different country,

00:56:52.751 --> 00:56:54.780
where you're kind of
done with that aspect.

00:56:54.780 --> 00:56:56.720
It turns out you
get very lonely.

00:56:56.720 --> 00:56:58.850
Also, if you have any
proclivity for depression,

00:56:58.850 --> 00:57:01.700
it comes out in spades,
because what you're doing

00:57:01.700 --> 00:57:03.866
is you're really sleep
depriving the body.

00:57:03.866 --> 00:57:05.740
Now the body can handle
only so much of that.

00:57:05.740 --> 00:57:07.406
Everybody that I've
ever worked with who

00:57:07.406 --> 00:57:09.770
wanted to do a
polyphasic sleep schedule

00:57:09.770 --> 00:57:12.140
stopped within three months,
because you can't even

00:57:12.140 --> 00:57:13.460
do dinner and a movie.

00:57:13.460 --> 00:57:16.730
You can go out, and then
your hour and 1/2 to 3 hours

00:57:16.730 --> 00:57:19.010
is up when you have
to take your next nap.

00:57:19.010 --> 00:57:22.277
And so it really becomes
socially very difficult to do.

00:57:22.277 --> 00:57:24.610
AUDIENCE: Probably a lot of
new moms and dads out there.

00:57:24.610 --> 00:57:26.350
MICHAEL BREUS: Yes.

00:57:26.350 --> 00:57:27.610
AUDIENCE: Advice for them?

00:57:27.610 --> 00:57:30.520
I remember something--
nap when the baby naps,

00:57:30.520 --> 00:57:33.220
but what are your top three
tips for new moms and dads?

00:57:33.220 --> 00:57:36.280
MICHAEL BREUS: So new moms and
new dads-- so first of all,

00:57:36.280 --> 00:57:37.030
this is--

00:57:37.030 --> 00:57:39.220
and it all depends
upon your baby.

00:57:39.220 --> 00:57:41.650
So we had two colicky babies.

00:57:41.650 --> 00:57:44.147
So both of my kids
had tremendous reflux

00:57:44.147 --> 00:57:45.730
to the point where
we had to have them

00:57:45.730 --> 00:57:48.820
on compounded Prilosec
to be able to keep them

00:57:48.820 --> 00:57:49.930
in a good spot.

00:57:49.930 --> 00:57:53.260
And so their sleep was
erratic until we did that.

00:57:53.260 --> 00:57:55.210
We actually did that
fairly early on,

00:57:55.210 --> 00:57:58.370
and we about got both of our
kids to sleep fairly easily.

00:57:58.370 --> 00:58:00.340
There's a great
program out there.

00:58:00.340 --> 00:58:01.515
It's called Baby Wise.

00:58:01.515 --> 00:58:02.890
That's what we
used in our house,

00:58:02.890 --> 00:58:05.290
and it's an eat,
sleep, play program,

00:58:05.290 --> 00:58:07.750
and it's really about the
consistency of the schedule.

00:58:07.750 --> 00:58:10.750
Kids' sleep invariably
doesn't get messed up.

00:58:10.750 --> 00:58:14.260
It's their parents that don't
keep a good, strict sleep

00:58:14.260 --> 00:58:14.980
schedule.

00:58:14.980 --> 00:58:18.094
So when Grandma and Grandpa's in
town, don't keep them up later.

00:58:18.094 --> 00:58:20.260
If Grandma and Grandpa's
flight got in at 8 o'clock,

00:58:20.260 --> 00:58:22.120
they don't get to see
the kids that night.

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:24.610
You don't keep them
up for that situation,

00:58:24.610 --> 00:58:26.890
because you end up with,
what is termed in our house,

00:58:26.890 --> 00:58:28.112
a meltdown.

00:58:28.112 --> 00:58:30.070
And that's a whole lot
of no fun for everybody.

00:58:30.070 --> 00:58:32.530
So the more consistent the
schedule is, the better.

00:58:32.530 --> 00:58:33.855
That's number one.

00:58:33.855 --> 00:58:35.980
Number two, if you do have
a situation where you've

00:58:35.980 --> 00:58:38.290
got a child that isn't
sleeping particularly well,

00:58:38.290 --> 00:58:41.140
you should use what I
call an on-call system.

00:58:41.140 --> 00:58:44.710
So one partner has
Monday, Wednesday, Friday.

00:58:44.710 --> 00:58:48.190
The other partner has
Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.

00:58:48.190 --> 00:58:50.740
And then Sunday,
you flip a coin.

00:58:50.740 --> 00:58:53.740
So if the baby is
crying, that individual

00:58:53.740 --> 00:58:56.710
is responsible for that as
opposed to both people waking

00:58:56.710 --> 00:58:58.060
up, not getting enough sleep.

00:58:58.060 --> 00:59:00.430
So that has a tendency
to work, or if you've

00:59:00.430 --> 00:59:02.855
got one person who's a lion
and one person who's a wolf,

00:59:02.855 --> 00:59:04.480
you can take different
shifts that way,

00:59:04.480 --> 00:59:06.880
where the lion can get up early,
and the wolf can stay up late.

00:59:06.880 --> 00:59:08.590
That has a tendency
to work as well.

00:59:08.590 --> 00:59:11.650
So it's really about managing
your time surrounding

00:59:11.650 --> 00:59:14.520
that situation, and checking out
that Baby Wise is pretty good.

00:59:14.520 --> 00:59:16.180
AUDIENCE: But Tom
from the other side

00:59:16.180 --> 00:59:17.805
of Mountain View
says, how long does it

00:59:17.805 --> 00:59:20.530
take to train your body
for a new sleeping routine?

00:59:20.530 --> 00:59:22.210
MICHAEL BREUS: So
it's interesting.

00:59:22.210 --> 00:59:23.860
If it's a sleeping
routine that works

00:59:23.860 --> 00:59:25.569
with your chronotype
and your genetics,

00:59:25.569 --> 00:59:26.860
then it doesn't take very long.

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:28.810
It'll adapt in usually
five to seven days.

00:59:28.810 --> 00:59:30.804
If you're trying to go
against your chronotype,

00:59:30.804 --> 00:59:33.220
so let's say you're a wolf and
you're trying to be a lion,

00:59:33.220 --> 00:59:35.770
it can take months to
be able to do that.

00:59:35.770 --> 00:59:37.270
And to be very
honest with you, it's

00:59:37.270 --> 00:59:39.250
not going to be
particularly successful.

00:59:39.250 --> 00:59:41.320
You really should try
to stick-- that's why

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:43.840
it's great to be a bear,
because bears kind of have it

00:59:43.840 --> 00:59:46.000
in the best spot, because
they can kind of move.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.416
And remember, you can be a
bear that wakes up a little bit

00:59:48.416 --> 00:59:50.495
early or a bear that stays
up a little bit late.

00:59:50.495 --> 00:59:52.120
So if you're following
your chronotype,

00:59:52.120 --> 00:59:53.630
it's not hard to
snap back into it.

00:59:53.630 --> 00:59:55.720
But when you're going
against your chronotype,

00:59:55.720 --> 00:59:58.810
it can take a long time, and
it isn't necessarily very

00:59:58.810 --> 00:59:59.980
successful.

